# Technical Architecture: Canvas-Based Interactive Presentation

## 1. Project Structure (Directory Layout)

```
src/
  app.ts                        # Entry point: mounts App.svelte
  App.svelte                    # Root component: layers background, canvas, UI overlay
  vite-env.d.ts                 # Vite type declarations

  lib/
    types.ts                    # All shared TypeScript interfaces/types
    constants.ts                # Magic numbers, defaults, breakpoints

    camera/
      camera.svelte.ts          # Camera state ($state class) + GSAP animation methods
      CameraViewport.svelte     # The CSS-transform container that moves content

    canvas/
      CanvasElement.svelte      # Wrapper: positions a content component at (x,y,scale)
      CanvasLayer.svelte         # The full canvas surface holding all CanvasElements

    focus/
      focus.svelte.ts           # Focus state ($state): which element is focused, transition state
      FocusOverlay.svelte       # Full-screen overlay that renders the focused component
      FocusTransition.svelte    # Handles the zoom-from-canvas-to-fullscreen animation

    walkthrough/
      walkthrough.svelte.ts     # Walkthrough engine state + step/play/pause logic
      WalkthroughControls.svelte # UI: play/pause, prev/next, progress indicator

    background/
      BackgroundCanvas.svelte   # <canvas> element + requestAnimationFrame render loop
      renderer.ts               # Pure functions: draw shapes, manage particles
      shapes.ts                 # Shape definitions (circles, blobs, grids, lines)

    ui/
      Toolbar.svelte            # Top-level presentation controls
      ProgressBar.svelte        # Visual progress through walkthrough steps
      KeyboardHandler.svelte    # Keyboard shortcut bindings

  content/
    elements.ts                 # Registry: maps element IDs to their Svelte components
    slides.config.ts            # Declarative config: element positions, scales, metadata
    walkthrough.config.ts       # Declarative config: walkthrough sequence

    slides/
      TitleSlide.svelte         # Example content component
      IntroSlide.svelte         # Example content component
      DemoVisualization.svelte  # Example interactive content component
      ...                       # Each "slide" or canvas element is its own component

    focused/
      TitleFocused.svelte       # Expanded/focused version of TitleSlide (optional)
      DemoFocusedView.svelte    # Interactive focused view of DemoVisualization
      ...                       # Focused variants (or the same component adapts via a prop)

index.html                      # Vite HTML entry
svelte.config.js                # Svelte compiler config
vite.config.ts                  # Vite + vite-plugin-svelte config
tsconfig.json                   # TypeScript config
package.json
```

**Rationale for this layout:**

- `lib/` holds all reusable systems (camera, focus, walkthrough, background, UI). These are the "engine."
- `content/` holds all presentation-specific authoring: which components exist, where they are placed, the walkthrough order. A presenter edits files here to build their presentation.
- State files use `.svelte.ts` extension so runes (`$state`, `$derived`, `$effect`) work outside `.svelte` files.
- Focused/expanded versions of elements can either be separate components or the same component receiving an `isFocused` prop. Both patterns are supported -- the `content/focused/` directory is optional for cases where the focused experience is substantially different from the canvas thumbnail.

---

## 2. Core Abstractions

### 2a. Camera / Viewport

The camera is represented as a point `(x, y)` with a `zoom` scale factor. The entire canvas of content is wrapped in a single `<div>` whose CSS `transform` is driven by the camera state.

**Rendering model:**

```
<div class="viewport">               <!-- overflow: hidden, fills the browser window -->
  <div class="canvas-layer"           <!-- transform: translate(-camX, -camY) scale(zoom) -->
       style="transform: ...">        <!-- GSAP animates this transform -->
    <CanvasElement ... />
    <CanvasElement ... />
  </div>
</div>
```

The transform is: `translate({-x * zoom + viewportWidth/2}px, {-y * zoom + viewportHeight/2}px) scale({zoom})`

This centers the camera target `(x, y)` in the middle of the viewport.

**Camera state class** (in `camera.svelte.ts`):

```typescript
class CameraState {
  x = $state(0);
  y = $state(0);
  zoom = $state(1);

  // Derived CSS transform string
  get transform(): string {
    // computed from x, y, zoom, and viewport dimensions
  }

  // Animate to a target using GSAP
  animateTo(target: CameraTarget, options?: AnimationOptions): gsap.core.Tween {
    return gsap.to(this, {
      x: target.x,
      y: target.y,
      zoom: target.zoom,
      duration: options?.duration ?? 1.5,
      ease: options?.ease ?? 'power2.inOut',
      onUpdate: () => { /* Svelte reactivity handles re-render */ }
    });
  }
}

export const camera = new CameraState();
```

Key insight: GSAP can animate plain JavaScript object properties. Because `CameraState` fields are `$state` runes, mutating them triggers Svelte reactivity. So `gsap.to(camera, { x: 100 })` will smoothly update the transform every frame, and Svelte will re-render the CSS transform binding. No extra plumbing needed.

**CameraViewport.svelte** binds the transform:

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { camera } from '$lib/camera/camera.svelte';
</script>

<div class="viewport">
  <div class="canvas-layer" style:transform={camera.transform}>
    <slot />
  </div>
</div>
```

### 2b. Canvas Element

A `CanvasElement` is a positioned wrapper. It takes a position, scale, and renders a content Svelte component inside.

```svelte
<!-- CanvasElement.svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  import type { CanvasElementConfig } from '$lib/types';
  import { focusState } from '$lib/focus/focus.svelte';

  let { config, children }: { config: CanvasElementConfig; children: any } = $props();

  function handleClick() {
    focusState.focusOn(config.id);
  }
</script>

<div
  class="canvas-element"
  style:transform="translate({config.x}px, {config.y}px) scale({config.scale})"
  style:width="{config.width}px"
  style:height="{config.height}px"
  onclick={handleClick}
  role="button"
  tabindex="0"
>
  {@render children()}
</div>
```

The content inside is a Svelte component, rendered by the parent that iterates over the element configs.

### 2c. Focus System

When a user clicks a canvas element, the focus system:

1. Records which element is being focused (by ID).
2. Calculates the element's current screen-space bounding rect.
3. Renders a `FocusOverlay` that starts at that bounding rect and animates (via GSAP) to fill the full viewport.
4. Once expanded, the focused component receives full interactivity.
5. Pressing Escape or a close button reverses the animation and returns to the canvas.

**Focus state** (in `focus.svelte.ts`):

```typescript
class FocusState {
  activeId = $state<string | null>(null);
  isTransitioning = $state(false);
  originRect = $state<DOMRect | null>(null);

  get isFocused(): boolean {
    return this.activeId !== null && !this.isTransitioning;
  }

  focusOn(elementId: string, rect: DOMRect) {
    this.originRect = rect;
    this.activeId = elementId;
    this.isTransitioning = true;
    // GSAP animation plays, then sets isTransitioning = false
  }

  unfocus() {
    this.isTransitioning = true;
    // Reverse animation, then sets activeId = null, isTransitioning = false
  }
}

export const focusState = new FocusState();
```

**FocusOverlay.svelte** conditionally renders above the canvas layer. The focused component is loaded dynamically from the element registry. This supports lazy loading via `import()`.

### 2d. Walkthrough Engine

The walkthrough is a sequence of "steps." Each step is a camera target (x, y, zoom) with optional metadata (title, duration, easing). The engine maintains the current step index and provides play/pause/step controls.

**Walkthrough state** (in `walkthrough.svelte.ts`):

```typescript
class WalkthroughEngine {
  steps = $state<WalkthroughStep[]>([]);
  currentIndex = $state(0);
  isPlaying = $state(false);
  private activeTween: gsap.core.Tween | null = null;

  get currentStep(): WalkthroughStep | undefined {
    return this.steps[this.currentIndex];
  }

  get progress(): number {
    return this.steps.length > 0 ? this.currentIndex / (this.steps.length - 1) : 0;
  }

  load(steps: WalkthroughStep[]) {
    this.steps = steps;
    this.currentIndex = 0;
  }

  async goToStep(index: number) {
    if (index < 0 || index >= this.steps.length) return;
    this.activeTween?.kill();
    this.currentIndex = index;
    const step = this.steps[index];
    this.activeTween = camera.animateTo(
      { x: step.x, y: step.y, zoom: step.zoom },
      { duration: step.duration, ease: step.ease }
    );
    await this.activeTween;
  }

  next() { this.goToStep(this.currentIndex + 1); }
  prev() { this.goToStep(this.currentIndex - 1); }

  async play() {
    this.isPlaying = true;
    while (this.isPlaying && this.currentIndex < this.steps.length - 1) {
      await this.goToStep(this.currentIndex + 1);
      if (this.isPlaying && this.currentStep?.pauseDuration) {
        await delay(this.currentStep.pauseDuration);
      }
    }
    this.isPlaying = false;
  }

  pause() {
    this.isPlaying = false;
    this.activeTween?.pause();
  }
}

export const walkthrough = new WalkthroughEngine();
```

The walkthrough reads from a declarative config and does not contain any presentation-specific logic. The config drives everything.

### 2e. Background Layer

A `<canvas>` element positioned behind all content via CSS `z-index`. It runs an independent `requestAnimationFrame` render loop. On each frame it reads the camera state (`camera.x`, `camera.y`, `camera.zoom`) and offsets its shapes with a parallax multiplier.

**BackgroundCanvas.svelte** (sketch):

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { camera } from '$lib/camera/camera.svelte';
  import { renderBackground } from '$lib/background/renderer';

  let canvasEl: HTMLCanvasElement;
  let animationId: number;

  $effect(() => {
    const ctx = canvasEl.getContext('2d')!;
    // Resize canvas to viewport
    const resize = () => {
      canvasEl.width = window.innerWidth;
      canvasEl.height = window.innerHeight;
    };
    resize();
    window.addEventListener('resize', resize);

    function loop() {
      renderBackground(ctx, {
        cameraX: camera.x,
        cameraY: camera.y,
        cameraZoom: camera.zoom,
        width: canvasEl.width,
        height: canvasEl.height,
      });
      animationId = requestAnimationFrame(loop);
    }
    animationId = requestAnimationFrame(loop);

    return () => {
      cancelAnimationFrame(animationId);
      window.removeEventListener('resize', resize);
    };
  });
</script>

<canvas bind:this={canvasEl} class="background-canvas"></canvas>
```

The `renderBackground` function in `renderer.ts` is a pure function that draws shapes. Each shape has a `parallaxFactor` (0 to 1) determining how much it shifts relative to camera movement. Factor 0 = static, factor 1 = moves 1:1 with camera, factor 0.5 = moves at half speed (creates depth).

---

## 3. Data Model (TypeScript Types)

All defined in `src/lib/types.ts`:

```typescript
// === Camera ===

export interface CameraTarget {
  x: number;       // World-space X coordinate to center on
  y: number;       // World-space Y coordinate to center on
  zoom: number;    // Zoom level (1 = 100%, 0.5 = zoomed out, 2 = zoomed in)
}

export interface AnimationOptions {
  duration?: number;       // Seconds (default: 1.5)
  ease?: string;           // GSAP easing string (default: 'power2.inOut')
}

// === Canvas Elements ===

export interface CanvasElementConfig {
  id: string;                     // Unique identifier
  x: number;                      // World-space X position
  y: number;                      // World-space Y position
  scale: number;                  // Element's scale on the canvas (1 = native size)
  width: number;                  // Logical width in pixels (before scale)
  height: number;                 // Logical height in pixels (before scale)
  component: string;              // Component identifier for the registry
  focusComponent?: string;        // Optional different component for focused state
  label?: string;                 // Human-readable label (for toolbar, accessibility)
  meta?: Record<string, unknown>; // Arbitrary metadata passed to the component
}

// === Walkthrough ===

export interface WalkthroughStep {
  id: string;                   // Unique step identifier
  targetElementId?: string;     // Optional: element this step focuses on (for highlighting)
  x: number;                    // Camera target X
  y: number;                    // Camera target Y
  zoom: number;                 // Camera target zoom
  duration?: number;            // Transition duration in seconds (default: 1.5)
  ease?: string;                // GSAP easing (default: 'power2.inOut')
  pauseDuration?: number;       // How long to pause at this step during auto-play (ms)
  label?: string;               // Step label for progress display
}

export interface WalkthroughConfig {
  name: string;
  description?: string;
  steps: WalkthroughStep[];
}

// === Background ===

export interface BackgroundShape {
  type: 'circle' | 'blob' | 'line' | 'grid' | 'ring';
  x: number;                  // World-space position
  y: number;
  size: number;               // Characteristic dimension
  color: string;              // CSS color string
  opacity: number;            // 0-1
  parallaxFactor: number;     // 0 = fixed, 1 = moves with camera, 0.3-0.7 typical
  blur?: number;              // Optional blur radius
  rotation?: number;          // Rotation in degrees
}

export interface BackgroundConfig {
  shapes: BackgroundShape[];
}

// === Focus ===

export interface FocusableElement {
  id: string;
  originRect: DOMRect;        // Bounding rect at time of click (screen-space)
}

// === Presentation Config (top-level) ===

export interface PresentationConfig {
  title: string;
  elements: CanvasElementConfig[];
  walkthrough: WalkthroughConfig;
  background: BackgroundConfig;
}
```

---

## 4. Declarative Configuration Files

### `src/content/slides.config.ts`

This is where the presenter defines what elements exist and where they sit on the canvas:

```typescript
import type { CanvasElementConfig } from '$lib/types';

export const elements: CanvasElementConfig[] = [
  {
    id: 'title',
    x: 0,
    y: 0,
    scale: 1,
    width: 800,
    height: 600,
    component: 'TitleSlide',
    label: 'Title',
  },
  {
    id: 'intro',
    x: 1200,
    y: 300,
    scale: 0.8,
    width: 700,
    height: 500,
    component: 'IntroSlide',
    label: 'Introduction',
  },
  {
    id: 'demo',
    x: 2500,
    y: -200,
    scale: 1.2,
    width: 900,
    height: 700,
    component: 'DemoVisualization',
    focusComponent: 'DemoFocusedView',
    label: 'Live Demo',
  },
];
```

### `src/content/walkthrough.config.ts`

The walkthrough sequence references camera positions (which often align with element positions but do not have to):

```typescript
import type { WalkthroughConfig } from '$lib/types';

export const walkthrough: WalkthroughConfig = {
  name: 'Main Presentation',
  steps: [
    {
      id: 'step-title',
      targetElementId: 'title',
      x: 0,
      y: 0,
      zoom: 1,
      duration: 0,           // Instant for the initial position
      pauseDuration: 3000,
      label: 'Title',
    },
    {
      id: 'step-intro',
      targetElementId: 'intro',
      x: 1200,
      y: 300,
      zoom: 1.2,
      duration: 2,
      ease: 'power3.inOut',
      pauseDuration: 5000,
      label: 'Introduction',
    },
    {
      id: 'step-demo',
      targetElementId: 'demo',
      x: 2500,
      y: -200,
      zoom: 0.8,
      duration: 2.5,
      ease: 'power2.inOut',
      label: 'Demo',
    },
  ],
};
```

### `src/content/elements.ts` (Component Registry)

This maps string component identifiers to actual Svelte components, supporting lazy loading:

```typescript
import type { Component } from 'svelte';

type ComponentLoader = () => Promise<{ default: Component }>;

export const componentRegistry: Record<string, ComponentLoader> = {
  TitleSlide: () => import('./slides/TitleSlide.svelte'),
  IntroSlide: () => import('./slides/IntroSlide.svelte'),
  DemoVisualization: () => import('./slides/DemoVisualization.svelte'),
  DemoFocusedView: () => import('./focused/DemoFocusedView.svelte'),
};
```

Using dynamic `import()` means Vite will code-split each content component into its own chunk, so only the visible/focused components are loaded.

